americans were troubled by food recalls the winter of 98-99.
in october, heinz recalled lead tainted baby food but no deaths were reported.
in november, ibf recalled beef possibly containing e-coli, which causes kidney failure and anemia.
in december, sara lee recalled deli meats after an outbreak of food poisoning, which killed 4 people, the at-risk population the elderly and pregnant women.
in january, thorn apple valley recalled meat products due to the possibility of listeria, which causes flu-like symptoms, especially threatening pregnant women.
possible listeria also saw oscar mayer recall deli meat in january.
****
according to the fda, between 1988 and 1998 there was a fivefold increase in food products recalled for e.coli and listeria bacteria and other life-threatening contaminants.
listeria was suspected or found in meat products of several companies, and one company's hot dogs were blamed for sickening 70 and killing 16.
in a normal year listeria is estimated to cause 1,850 illnesses resulting in 425 deaths.
the agriculture department urged consumers to return all recalled products and to properly handle, cook, and store food.
it was considering requirements for more industry testing.
the president proposed giving increased authority to food agencies.
****
from october 1998 to february, food produced in the united states was tainted with listeria, e. coli, enterotoxigenic e. coli, and lead, causing recalls of products.
listeria caused nine recalls of meat with one producer causing 82 illnesses and 12 adult deaths.
one recall for e. coli and one recall of baby food containing lead resulted in no illnesses.
in july 1998 president clinton asked for more money and authority for the food and drug administration, to facilitate faster recalls, warning labels, and a food safety research institute.
rigid food safety practices are the best way to avoid infection.
****
there has been a sudden increase in u.s. food recalls because of centralized food processing and wide distribution.
tainted foods present a major health threat to the elderly, pregnant women, the very young, and those with weakened immune systems.
the bacteria are found in hot dogs, cold cuts, and soft cheeses.
in response to an outbreak of food poisoning, the government and/or company can recall the products and stop production operations, but the consumer must check product codes, cook meats to 165 degrees, separate raw foods and uncooked meats, and wash hands and cutting tools thoroughly.
