australia strongly opposes japan's plan to increase its authorized kill of whales in antarctic waters at the annual meeting of the international whaling commission opening may 30, 2005 in south korea.
australian attorney general philip ruddock says australia would lead a diplomatic effort to have a south pacific whale sanctuary, but would not try to board japanese ships.
prime minister john howard said australia was working with the united states, new zealand and england to convince japan to reconsider its proposal.
japan is believed to have the votes to get its proposal approved.
****
japan plans to seek permission to expand its so-called research whaling program when the international whaling commission ( iwc) meets in late may, intending to nearly double its annual catch of minke whales and to hunt endangered humpback and fin whales.
australia, new zealand, and conservationists strongly oppose japan's plan to expand whaling in the australia-declared whale sanctuary in antarctic waters, but they have no legal recourse to stop it.
australia's prime minister appealed directly to his japanese counterpart, urging him to reconsider his position.
he dispatched lobbying missions to europe and the pacific to rally iwc votes against japan's plans.
****
japan wants to nearly double its annual antarctic catch of 440 minke whales and catch 80 each of endangered humpback and fin whales.
it will seek approval at the 2005 international whaling commission meeting.
pro-whaling countries may have a voting majority for the first time since 1986, when the iwc halted commercial whaling.
in 1987 japan resumed under a research-whaling loophole.
its 2000-ton catch brings in $52 million.
australia opposes whaling in its antarctic whale sanctuary.
whale-watching is a major tourist industry for new zealand and australia.
australia forbade a suit against the japanese whaling company, preferring a diplomatic solution.
****
australia and new zealand are strongly opposed to japan's plans to seek approval at the international whaling commission ( iwc) to enlarge its catch of whales in antarctica.
japan wants to almost double its catch of minke whales and add humpback and fin whales, both of which are endangered.
there is a moratorium on commercial whaling, but japan hunts them under a loophole that allows ``research whaling ''.
it does not recognize australia's claim of sovereignty over australian antarctic territory.
whaling opponents fear that pro-whaling countries like japan and norway could get a majority vote at the iwc.
