in central europe, the worst snowfall in 50 years triggered february avalanches that hit ski resorts and towns in austria's western states of triol and vorarlberg, blocking roads and stranding tens of thousands.
the galtuer resort, near the swiss border, was hit by two consecutive avalanches on february 22 and 23, and early reports said at least 16 were dead, 30 injured and 29 missing.
avalanche deaths and injuries were also reported in valzur and ischgl.
austria established a center in landeck for sending supplies and receiving victims by helicopter.
avalanches have killed 60 this year throughout europe.
****
in february 1999, austria suffered its worst avalanches in 45 years because of almost unparalleled amounts of snow and high winds whipping it into drifts and making it unstable on the crust of earlier snow.
in the ski resort of galtuer near the swiss border, 16 were confirmed killed and 20-30 were missing from two avalanches on consecutive days.
the first avalanche was 15-20 feet high and 300-500 feet wide; the second was 45 feet high.
in other avalanches, in nearby ischgl, one woman was killed and six others were missing, and in valzur two were killed.
****
avalanches on 23 and 24 february 1999 struck an austrian ski region, including villages of galtuer, valzur, gargellen, and ischgl.
at least 25 people were killed with dozens missing.
houses and cars were crushed by snow walls as large as 45 'deep and 600 wide.
thousands of tourists were stranded.
at first snow and wind limited all but local rescue attempts.
by the second day 200 army troops were helping, and a dozen helicopters transported injured to a hospital in landeck, where rescue headquarters was located.
these avalanches were set off by the fiercest alpine snowstorms in 50 years.
****
the worst snow storm in 50 years and high winds are causing avalanches in austria.
the galtuer ski resort area was hit by avalanches on february 23 and 24, 1999.
ten houses were crushed, 16 people dead, 17 injured, and 15 missing.
initial rescue operations were by locals then austrian troops and helicopters were brought in.
the united states, germany and switzerland offered additional helicopters.
an emergency command post was established to take victims and send food and supplies.
also on february 24, an avalanche struck valzur, killing two.
on february 22, an avalanche buried two, one dying, in gargallen.
