****
the federal trial of unabomber suspect theodore kaczynski began with jury selection in sacramento on 12 november 1997.
turned in by mother and brother, the former math instructor was arrested in april 1996, suspected of terrorizing the country in a campaign against technology between 1978-1995, mailing bombs which killed three people and injured twenty-three.
federal defense attorneys, quinn denvir and judy clark, entered a plea of innocent, seeking a separate new jersey trial incorporated into the sacramento trial.
attorney general janet reno approved seeking the death penalty.
u.s. district judge burrell allowed kaczynski's journals to be used as evidence.
****
in sacramento, theodore kaczynski faces a 10-count federal indictment for 4 of the 16 mail bomb attacks attributed to the unabomber in which two people were killed.
if found guilty, he faces a death penalty.
kaaczynski also faces new jersey charges for another fatal bombing.
he has pleaded innocent to all charges.
u.s. district judge garland burrell jr. presides in sacramento.
the trial may take 6 months.
attorneys made opening statements in january 1998.
in new jersey, judge debevoisse heard defense arguments for combining all charges at a single sacramento trial.
kaczynski's defense attorneys are quin denvir and judy clarke.
****
the so-called unabomber, 54-year-old former mathematics professor theodore kaczynski, accused of killing three and injuring 23 during a campaign against technology between 1978 and 1995, is awaiting trial in sacramento, california.
jury selection is scheduled to begin november 12, 1997, and the trial is expected to last six months.
in april 1996, kaczynski was arrested by the fbi at his remote cabin in montana after being turned in by his brother david.
authorities had been searching unsuccessfully for him for 18 years.
kaczynski intends to plead innocent at trial, and prosecutors are unsure if they will seek the death penalty.
****
theodore kaczynski is suspected of being the unabomber, the mail-bomb terrorist who killed three and injured 23 others in 16 bombings over an 18-year period.
kaczynski is charged with four of the unabomber's 16 attacks, including two fatalities in california.
he is also charged with a fatal bombing in new jersey.
he has pled innocent in the first trial, which will be held in sacremento and address the california deaths.
prosecutors say they have a lot of evidence, including kaczynski's incriminating diaries, which defense lawyers quin denvir and judy clarke tried unsuccessfully to have excluded from the trial.
****
yearlong uneasiness in baluchistan erupted on 17 march 2005, a six vehicle convoy attacked by bugti tribal rebels.
the death toll in the town of dera bugti in the southwest pakistan province was eight soldiers with seven wounded, and twenty-two tribesmen killed and seventy wounded.
seventeen hindus also died and their temple damaged.
the frontier corps then sent troops and two helicopters to quell the uprising.
the goal of the rebels was greater autonomy and increased benefits from the region's resources.
three thousand government civilians then fled the area, the same number of bugti women and children also fleeing.
****
on march 17, 2005 thirty people were killed and more than 70 wounded in fierce gun battles between pakistani soldiers and bugti tribesmen in the southwestern province of baluchistan.
the exchange of rockets and mortar shells continued all day after the rebels ambushed a pakistani convoy in the tribal stronghold of dera bugti.
a senior official there reported about 5000 armed tribesmen positioned in mountains outside the town where both sides are evacuating residents.
baluchistan has for more than a year experienced attacks by tribesmen demanding more revenue in compensation for natural resources extracted from their territory.
****
in baluchistan on thursday, march 17, 2005, in an escalation of violence after a january 2nd rape, bugti tribesmen attacked a pakistani frontier corps convoy and shelled a military base.
a cease-fire ended day-long fighting in dera bugti.
up to 45 died.
others died from bombs on trains ( placed by the baluchistan liberation army), in turbat and quetta, and 39 at a fatahpur shrine.
nawab akbar bugti warned dera bugti residents to leave and 3000 did.
1500-5000 tribesmen gathered in nearby mountains waiting to attack government installations and troops.
tribesmen want more autonomy and increased benefits from baluchistan's natural resources.
****
rebellion has increased dramatically in baluchistan, where tribesmen demand greater royalties from gas reserves and object to the army's establishing new garrisons.
rebels attacked a paramilitary convoy and a base near dera bugti on 17 march, killing up to 30 people and injuring more than 70.
two trains were bombed killing 2 and injuring 8, a bomb killed 39 at the memorial of a muslim sufi saint, and 17 minority hindus were killed when their temple was hit by rockets thousands of government employees and their families, and thousands of women and children of local tribesmen, fled their homes.
****
ephedra, also called ma huang, is an herbal stimulant containing the chemical ephedrine.
it is an ingredient in a variety of weight-loss, energy-boosting, and body building supplements.
it can be dangerous to people with certain underlying health problems.
side effects include anxiety, insomnia, hypertension, tachycardia, psychosis, kidney damage, dependency, heart attack, and stroke.
it is linked to over 12 deaths worldwide.
ephedra can produce an amphetamine-like rush, and is used to make methamphetamine.
having received hundreds of complaints about ephedra, the fda has issued warnings and is considering establishing limits on its use.
several states have banned ephedrine-containing supplements.
****
the asian herb ephedra contains stimulants known chemically as ephedrine.
pure ephedrine can be used to make methamphedamine, a highly addictive street drug, but in controlled dosages it is prescribed for colds and asthma.
as an herbal dietary supplement, outside fda control, it can decrease appetite, improve concentration, raise metabolism, and enhance sexual performance.
but it can be habit-forming; reports of deaths and other negative side effects ( including anxiety, insomnia, hypertension, psychosis, kidney damage, heart attack, and stroke) have led to the rare case where the government takes action against an herbal product, considering regulations on sales, labeling, and dosage.
****
ephedra ( ephedrine) is the herb ma huang used in chinese medicine.
it appears in many weight-loss, energy-boosting, and body-building supplements.
ephedra stimulates the central nervous system and heart.
people think natural means good but ephedra can harm people with hypertension.
hundreds of adverse reactions have been reported, including 40 deaths.
classed as a dietary supplement, ephedra is not subject to regulation.
industry lobbyists protecting highly popular and profitable products defeated the fda's 1997 efforts to set dosage standards.
the ftc took action claiming false advertising.
china tightened controls on production.
college and olympic authorities and several states banned ephedrine-containing supplements.
****
ephedra, a diet supplement and herb containing ephedrine, is a heart stimulant that may cause physical and mental problems, and death.
producers claim it increases energy, helps take off weight, tones muscles, and increases sexual sensation.
millions of people, especially athletes, are taking this supplement.
its unsupervised sale was made possible by 1994 legislation which removed food and drug administration ( fda) oversight of diet products.
the deaths of 40 and incidents involving 800 have caused the fda to try to limit supplements to 8 mgs per dose, 24 mgs per day.
chinese and texas authorities are also concerned.
****
the recent 26 december 2004 tsunami in the indian ocean with destruction of mangrove forests has highlighted their environmental importance.
the trees grow in swampy coastal areas, providing buffers against tsunami caused erosion, providing nurseries for many fish species, providing wood for fuel, boats, and homes, also providing sanctuaries for shorebirds and crab eating monkeys.
vietnam, india, and indonesia have long recognized their benefits and have ongoing programs for their protection.
a u.n. agriculture agency pushed for early rehabilitation of mangroves damaged by the tsunami, but warned against overforestation to the detriment of other ecosystems.
****
mangrove forests thrive near the mouths of large river deltas.
their roots collect sediment and slow the water's flow, protecting the coastline, preventing erosion, and gradually extending the coastline seaward.
mangroves also give inhabitants timber, fuel wood and thatch for houses.
up to half of the world's mangrove swamps have disappeared in the last 20-30 years because of the development of tourist resorts and shrimp farms.
the asian tsunami of dec. 26, 2004 gave many examples of shore areas saved by mangroves and of lives and structures destroyed where mangroves had earlier been removed.
****
mangrove forests create nurseries for many fish and provide habitat for birds, monkeys, fishing cats, and crustaceans.
they provide construction and fuel materials for humans.
mangrove roots collect sediment and prevent erosion.
in the 2004 indian ocean tsunami, mangroves lessened onshore damage and their absence exacerbated it.
the tsunami uprooted mangrove forests from sri lanka to thailand and damaged their ecosystems.
eased regulations allowing development of tourist, transportation, and aquaculture facilities have caused half the world's mangrove swamps to disappear in the last 30 years.
authorities are studying mangrove-forest rehabilitation and introduction.
idled fishermen are planting mangroves in tamil nadu.
****
mangroves grow in thickets along tropical coastlines with tangled roots above ground and salt-filtering taproots.
acting as shock absorbers, they are vital in protecting the shore.
they teem with life, providing a safe haven for fish, birds, crustaceans, and shellfish.
up to half of the world's mangroves have disappeared in the last 20-30 years because of the development of tourist resorts and commercial prawn farming.
there are now fewer than 40,000 acres left.
the un has called for the rehabilitation of mangroves damaged by the recent tsunami, noting that there was much less damage in mangrove-protected areas.
****
on november 28, escaping natural gas posed risk of explosion on an oil-drilling platform in the north sea.
most workers were evacuated and oil production halted.
operated by statoil, norway's state-controlled oil company, this platform also processes oil from nearby vigdis field.
statoil thought production could resume in a month but norway's petroleum safety authority has approval authority and said that damage may be greater than first believed.
a month-and-a-half after the closing, statoil asked to partially resume production though it would take time to reach even limited production goals.
statoil is losing $1.8 million daily.
****
a november 2004 natural gas leak on norwegian statoil's snorre a oil platform in the north sea caused the shutdown of production from snorre a and neighboring platform vigdis, resulting in a cut in oil output of 205,000 barrels a day for norway and costing statoil 1.4 million euros daily.
the leak, which could have caused a catastrophic explosion, was contained 18 hours after it was reported.
there was no evidence of oil leaked into the water, and there were no injuries.
statoil's request to restart operations would not be granted until an inspection by the norwegian petroleum safety authority.
****
a gas leak in an injection shaft shut down norway's snorre a oil platform in the north sea nw of bergen around 7pm november 28, 2004.
because of explosion risk, 180 workers were evacuated.
operator statoil pumped in drilling mud to push back gas and seal the leak with cement, in constant contact with technical experts.
snorre a and neighboring vigdis were shut down for over a month, costing 205,000 barrels of oil daily.
an oversight agency needed to approve resumption but rough weather delayed inspections.
a gas leak that shut down marathon's brae alpha platform november 27th appeared unrelated.
****
on november 28, 2004 norway's statoil closed the snorra and vigdis oil platforms in the north sea.
a gas leak caused the snorra to become unstable and it could explode.
the leak was contained then statoil began pumping drilling mud into the injection well.
this closure dropped norway's production by 205,000 barrels per day, costing statoil $1.8 million a day.
statoil hoped to resume operations by december 31, but bad weather and safety authority approval delayed plans.
statoil requested approval on january 13.
another north sea leak caused marathon oil corp to close the brae alpha platform on november 30.
****
on july 25, 2005 south korean president roh moo-hyun called for a ``thorough ''investigation by the national intelligence service ( nis) into allegations that intelligence officials had, in 1997, illegally taped conversations between hong seok-hyun, south korean ambassador to the u.s. and lee hak-soo, a high ranking official of samsung, the country's largest business conglomerate.
revelation of the recorded conversations involving an illegal political slush fund caused hong to resign as ambassador.
on august 5 nis released interim results from its ongoing investigation admitting it had taped influential figures as late as 2002, but not under president roh's administration.
****
the south korean president initiated an investigation of illegal wire-tapping by nis ( the intelligence service).
this produced 274 illegal recordings, and led to the arrests of a retired nis official, who had kept an illegal tape, and the businessman to whom he gave it, who then leaked it to the media.
it resulted in the resignation of the ambassador to the u.s., heard on the tape in an incriminating conversation with a samsung executive, discussing allegedly illegal political contributions.
samsung apologized and filed a libel suit.
nis' current chief admitted his agency's earlier bugging operations.
the media are being questioned.
****
in 2005 south korean president roh moo-hyun called for a probe into illegal wiretapping by the national intelligence service after a 1997 recording was leaked to the media.
kong un-yong, former nis special wiretapping unit head, attempted suicide after the announcement.
he left a note saying he kept recordings at home after retirement and gave the tape to a korean-american businessman, who leaked copies after his blackmail attempt failed.
the businessman was arrested.
nis director kim seung-gyu publicly apologized for the wiretapping, which continued until 2002, long after it was ordered ended in 1998.
he said the nis would reform.
****
in late july south korean tv and newspapers released illegally taped private conversations between a major newspaper publisher and a samsung executive, in which they discussed samsung's providing a $3 million slush fund for candidates in the 1997 elections.
nis apologized for illegal wiretapping, which continued until march 2002.
samsung apologized for the scandal.
the newspaper publisher, hong, appointed ambassador to the us in february, resigned.
a former intelligence official was arrested after trying to commit suicide.
he had given the recordings to a korean-american businessman who leaked copies to the media after failing to blackmail samsung.
****
amphibians, a species class including frogs, toads, salamanders, and caecilians, are declining world-wide, a development beginning in the late 1980's.
scientists view amphibians as ``canaries in the coal mine '', their demise possibly presaging decline of human life.
threats to amphibian survival include chemically polluted streams, destruction of rain forests, pesticides which can trigger hermaphroditism, climate change, thinning ozone layer, over harvesting for food and medicine, and even the closing of australia's only frog hospital.
remedies to decline include creation of parks and reserves, reducing climate change emissions, and breeding amphibians in captivity to sustain vulnerable species.
****
the rapidly declining number of frogs and other amphibians indicates environmental degradation that may affect all of us.
amphibians' permeable skins and habitats make them an important indicator of environmental quality.
one study found that 32% face extinction.
reasons for this include habitat decline ( water pollution, pesticides), over-harvesting for food and medicine, and increasing number of lethal and previously unrecognized frog diseases.
corrective actions include reducing emissions that contribute to climate change, creating parks and ecological reserves, and breeding frogs in captivity in order to sustain vulnerable species.
****
frog populations are declining worldwide due to deforestation, pollution, habitat loss, climate change, pesticides, parasites, non-native predators, the fungal disease chytridiomycosis, hermaphroditic frogs caused by ddt and atrazine, and over-harvesting for food and medicine.
the large cuban tree frog has invaded florida and devours smaller native frogs.
rare protected frogs are smuggled to european collectors.
frogs are important sentinels for environmental problems because of the sensitivity of their permeable skin.
creating ecological reserves, reducing emissions that contribute to climate change, and breeding frogs in captivity can help sustain species.
china creates ``frog freeways ''to help frogs escape from ditches.
****
frogs are disappearing at an alarming rate across the globe.
frogs are very important indicators of environmental change because their permeable skin is extremely sensitive to any changes.
they are threatened mainly by climate change and fungal disease, but also by pollution, deforestation, habitat loss, and harvesting for food and medicines.
there was also a dramatic increase in the number of hermaphrodites among frogs during the period when ddt and other pesticides were widely used.
to reverse this trend, we must protect their habitat in part by creating parks and reserves, reduce emissions, and breed them in captivity.
****
the veterans administration recognizes 10 diseases and the birth defect spina bifida as linked or possibly linked to agent orange.
any american who served in the war is automatically presumed to have been exposed to the defoliant.
agent orange was sprayed on jungles by us planes for 10 years to strip away cover from north vietnamese troops.
vietnam estimates that up to 2 million of its citizens suffer from agent orange-associated ailments, but its studies are discounted by western experts for lack of stringent methodology.
vietnam has launched a support fund, managed by the red cross, for agent orange victims.
****
agent orange is a defoliant used during the vietnam war to strip away the protective cover used by north vietnamese troops.
it has a lingering toxic component called dioxin, which has been linked to three kinds of cancer and chemical acne among the vietnamese and in americans fighting there, as well as birth defects in their children.
however, it is virtually impossible to determine which ailments came directly from agent orange.
research continues and u.s. law requires review every two years.
dioxin caused widespread environmental damage in vietnam; precautions are taken as suspected caches of dioxin are still being found.
****
from 1961 to 1971, american planes sprayed agent orange over parts of south vietnam to deny cover and sustenance for north vietnamese troops.
cancer-causing dioxin was inadvertently created during agent orange's manufacturing process.
agent orange is proven linked to birth defects including spina bifida; cancers soft-tissue sarcoma, non-hodgkin's lymphoma, and hodgkin's disease; and skin disease cholaracne.
an estimated 300,000 vietnamese victims include local residents, soldiers, and their children and grandchildren.
deformed vietnamese children are cared for in scattered ``peace villages ''.
the u.s. first refused some veterans' claims but now assumes all 2 million who served in the war were exposed.
****
the u.s. sprayed 19 million gallons of the defoliant agent orange ( containing dioxin) over south vietnam from 1962 to 1971, exposing two million vietnamese and 2.1 million u.s. military.
vietnamese veterans and civilians have various ailments and their children suffer from physical deformities and mental retardation.
the sickest are tended in special villages.
in 1999 vietnam began a survey to find the exact number of sufferers, but 70,000 are known the u.s. veterans affairs department acknowledges agent orange can cause three cancers, chloracne, spinal bifida in offspring, and seven other diseases.
they have received 92,000 claims and treated 50,000 cases.
****
victor yushchenko, a candidate for ukrainian president, first entered a vienna clinic on 10 september 2004, seriously ill and unable to walk.
this and subsequent clinic visits determined positively that dioxin, a waste product of industrial processes, had been ingested, possibly from spiked soup, which along with questionably refrigerated sushi yushchenko was served the night of 5 september at a meeting in kiev.
yushchenko, whose face shown in many newsphotos was swollen and discolored, accused his political opposition of the poisoning.
yushchenko lost the election but fraud findings led to another election in december.
****
in early december, austria's rudolfinerhaus clinic announced that tests confirmed that orally administered dioxin had poisoned viktor yushchenko.
he was admitted to the clinic twice in recent months in serious condition.
yushchenko is in a contested election for president of the ukraine, running against the current prime minister.
a runoff election will be held december 26.
after dioxin poisoning was confirmed, the ukraine prosecutor general reinstituted a criminal investigation.
yushchenko believes the poisoning was political reprisal and the aim was to kill him.
the u.s. has denied charges that it financially supports yushchenko whose political rival is pro-russian.
****
vienna doctors confirmed that ukrainian opposition leader victor yushchenko was poisoned by dioxin possibly put in his food.
yushchenko alleged an assassination attempt by government officials who feared he would defeat prime minister viktor yanukovych in presidential runoff elections.
yushchenko had dinner and drinks sept. 5th with security service head smeshko and his deputy.
he had headaches the next day and was hospitalized sept. 10th.
his skin became disfigured, his digestive tract was dotted with ulcers, and excruciating back pain required huge doses of morphine.
doctors were optimistic about his recovery.
ukrainian prosecutors reopened a criminal investigation into his poisoning.
****
victor yushchenko, ukrainian candidate for president, became ill on september 6, 2004, after dining with security service officials.
yushchenko suffered severe pain, internal bleeding, and facial disfigurement.
he entered an austrian clinic where doctors suspected poison.
yushchenko accused ``government officials. ''
yushchenko won a november run-off election, but results were negated and a december run-off was scheduled.
on december 10 austrians confirmed he was poisoned with dioxin.
a criminal investigation was reopened with strong us urging.
this attack apparently was to prevent his election victory.
he had promised to investigate past assassinations and the administration accused him of us financial backing.
****
the chesapeake bay's maryland oyster has been decimated by over-fishing, pollution and parasites.
oyster harvests dropped 92% in five years.
as a revenue source, oysters declined from $65 million annually to $500,000.
there are efforts to save or replace the oyster.
at managed reserves, maryland plants disease free oysters, gives them 3 years to grow, then allows harvesting.
research continues on the asian oyster, successfully grown in seattle waters, to see if they will be disease resistant and not harm the bay's ecosystem.
virginia and maryland governors will decide whether more research is needed when study findings are presented.
****
maryland oysters, the shining jewels of chesapeake bay, are becoming an endangered species.
the annual haul in 2003 was about 23,000 bushels compared to 80,000 in 1993 and 2 million plus in the 1980's.
maryland and virginia have taken steps to protect native oysters, but both are considering introducing the chinese oyster as a replacement.
as optimism about the chinese oyster has grown in the administration of gov.
robert ehrlich ( r-md), pessimism has spread among scientists.
maryland has successfully spawned and raised native oysters in managed reserves under scientific supervision but the process is slow and limited in scope.
****
oysters are disappearing from the chesapeake bay.
once bringing $65 million into maryland annually, they now bring but $500,000.
they also brought tourists and, most importantly, filtered the water of the bay.
their decline is attributed to over-harvesting, pollution, and two parasites appearing in the 1960's, one brought by asian oysters.
maryland, virginia, and the national government are spending millions to save the oyster.
research centers harvest seed and maintain managed reserves.
sewer system discharge and farm run-off must be controlled.
some want to introduce a new chinese specie to the bay, but others fear the consequences of this move.
****
chesapeake bay oysters have almost vanished because of pollution, over harvesting, and two parasites.
they are critical to the health of the bay because they filter the water virginia and maryland have been spending several million dollars every year to restore native populations, and more than 330 million oysters have been planted since 2000.
virginia and maryland are considering introducing an asian oyster but others want more studies done on potential impact, since they could bring new diseases and problems and could squeeze out the native oysters altogether.
moreover it would be impossible to remove them once they were introduced.
****
after being dormant for eighteen years, mount saint helens in washington erupted with steam and ash on 1 october 2005 after a series of earthquakes beginning a week earlier.
on 2 october, another burst of steam preceded hour long tremors.
next day, a tremor lasting twenty-five minutes prompted scientists to warn of a more serious eruption but the nearest residents thirty miles from the crater were not evacuated.
an observatory five miles from the crater was evacuated and aircraft were diverted from the area.
tourists, however, flocked to the area, many disappointed at the minimal fireworks from the crater.
****
mount st. helens in southwest washington state erupted violently on may 18, 1980 killing 57people, destroying 200 homes and coating much of the northwest with 520 million tons of ash.
seismic activity beginning on sept. 23, 2004 released more energy than at any time since 1980 and on october 1 the volcano burped a tall column of steam and ash.
seismic activity ceased briefly but resumed.
on oct. 2 scientists warned of a more serious eruption threatening life and property.
officials evacuated an observatory 5 miles from the crater and moved tourists to a lookout point several miles below.
****
beginning september 23, 2004, building pressures caused several earthquakes per minute ( up to strength 3.3) on mt.
st. helens in sw washington.
on friday, october 1st, a 10,000-foot column of steam and ash rose for 24 minutes.
this first eruption since 1986 punched a hole in the dome's ice.
no evacuations were ordered.
close monitoring continued.
on saturday an observatory five miles away was evacuated as earthquakes intensified.
around noon the volcano emitted a burst of steam followed by a crater landslide, rotten-egg smell, and a 50-minute tremor believed caused by rising magma.
at 3am sunday a 25-minute tremor occurred.
****
a level 3 ( the highest) volcano alert is issued for mount st. helens, washington.
in late october 2004 there were seismic rumblings.
on november 1 a 24-minute 1,000-foot plume appeared.
after more earthquakes, on november 2 there was a brief shot of steam and a 50-minute low-frequency tremor.
on november 3, a second tremor lasted 25 minutes.
mount st. helens erupted in 1980 killing 57.
tourists gathered.
an observatory 5 miles away was evacuated, but towns have not been evacuated.
scientists are monitoring the volcano with aircraft ( sampling the air and detecting hot spots), seismographs, and global positioning sensors.
****
in amsterdam, on 2 november 2004, theo van gogh, a descendant of the famed artist, was killed by a muslim extremist, in apparent retaliation for the showing on tv of theo's film ``submission '', which depicted the spousal abuse of four muslim women.
the dual dutch and moroccan assailant, not further identified, who left a note attached to van gogh, was arrested immediately after the attack.
the shooting heightened already strained relations between the million muslim minority and the normally tolerant but now threatened dutch.
immigrant groups condemned the slaying but emphasized assimilation was difficult when feeling unwanted.
****
november 2, dutch filmmaker theo van gogh was murdered on an amsterdam street.
his film ``submission, ''about the treatment of women in islamic society, outraged the muslim community.
a note left on the body called for holy war.
police quickly apprehended the suspect, a muslim of dual dutch and moroccan citizenship.
eight suspects were arrested in connection with the murder.
dutch muslim groups in amsterdam condemned the killing and pleaded for dialog.
some 20,000 people gathered in a noisy tribute to van gogh, while opinion polls showed many dutch feel threatened by the nearly one million muslims in the netherlands.
****
dutch filmmaker theo van gogh, known for his controversial views, was murdered on an amsterdam street on 2 november 2004, in broad daylight.
the assailant, of dual dutch/moroccan nationality, was captured and arrested after a shootout in which he and a policeman were wounded.
the motive is believed to be radical islamic views; the filmmaker had received numerous death threats following the airing of an anti-muslim movie.
whilst admitting van gogh's views were hurtful, muslim groups condemned the killing and called for calm.
meanwhile, thousands gathered for a raucous memorial rally.
police later arrested eight associates of the assailant.
****
theo van gogh, 47, died in amsterdam, the netherlands, on november 2, 2004.
the dutch filmmaker and distant relative of vincent van gogh was shot and stabbed by a 26 year old dutch/moroccan muslim.
the police immediately arrested the assassin, although both he and one of the police were shot.
van gogh was vocally anti-muslim and had been receiving death threats.
fear of further polarization and intolerance in the dutch society spread.
twenty-thousand attended a memorial service and dutch and muslin leaders expressed concern, calling for calm and dialogue.
police interviewed witnesses, searched apartments, took evidence and arrested eight muslims.
****
after 2 months of testimony, attorneys presented closing statements in the murder trial of robert blake, actor, which now goes to the jury.
accused of murdering his wife of less than a year, blake pleaded innocent.
prosecuting attorney samuels emphasized blakes' dislike of his wife, his desire for a divorce, and allegations he'd tried a murder-for-hire scheme.
defense attorney schwartzbach cast doubt on the veracity of witnesses in that scheme and emphasized lack of physical evidence.
if convicted, blake faces a life sentence plus 9 years if found guilty on the attempted murder-for-hire.
blake did not testify.
****
actor robert blake is on trial in van nuys superior court charged with murder of his wife bonnie lee bakley on may 4, 2001 and two counts of solicitation of murder.
the prosecutor, deputy los angeles county district attorney shelly l. samuels, has relied heavily on two stuntmen who claim blake solicited them to kill his wife.
blake has pleaded not guilty.
his lawyer, m. gerald schwartzbach, has emphasized the lack of evidence against blake, attacked the competence of the l.a. police department investigation and demeaned the believability of the stuntmen.
closing arguments in the trial ended march 4, 2005.
****
actor robert blake, 71, is accused of shooting his wife, bonny lee bakley, on may 4, 2001 in a car parked outside a restaurant which blake says he had re-entered to retrieve a handgun.
blake is charged with murder, solicitation to murder, and the special circumstance of lying in wait.
blake pleaded not guilty and is free on $1.5 million bail.
prosecutor deputy la county da shellie l. samuels claims blake hated bakley because she tricked him into marrying her and he wanted custody of their daughter rosie.
he killed her after he could n't hire others to do it.
****
robert blake, a 71 year-old actor, is on trial for shooting his wife, bonny lee bakley, on may 4, 2001, in his car after dining at an italian restaurant.
he is charged with murder, two counts of solicitation of murder, and special circumstance of lying in wait.
if convicted he would face life in prison.
he pled not guilty.
the trial is occurring in the van nuys superior court of los angles.
deputy district attorney shellie samuels is prosecuting and m. gerald schwartzbach is the defense attorney.
closing arguments for the 2-month trial began on february 26, 2005.
****
coral reefs provide seafood and livelihood for one billion asians alone, many from impoverished areas.
over 58% of the world's coral reefs are endangered because of pollution, over-fishing, disease, and climate change.
reefs suffer from hurricanes and el nino-triggered bleaching.
coral reef damage from the late december indian ocean tsunamis is yet to be assessed.
about 30% of the world's coral reefs are healthy, down from 41% two years ago.
about two-fifths of those damaged in the 1998 el nino bleaching have since recovered.
taiwan is constructing artificial reefs to act as foundations to support new living coral colonies.
****
among the world's oldest and most diverse forms of life, coral reefs provide food and shelter to fish as well as humans, protect shores from erosion, and provide economic livelihoods based on fishing and tourism.
more than 58% of the world's coral reefs are threatened by disease, pollution, over-fishing, weather and tidal conditions, coastal development, and encroachment of introduced species.
their destruction impacts over one billion people and threatens over 15,000 species with extinction.
protection efforts include fishing restrictions, coral reef trade limitations, artificial reefs, satellite monitoring, and possibly the introduction of more heat-tolerant co-habiting species.
****
coral reefs are threatened worldwide.
only 30 percent are healthy.
reefs are beautiful, but also critical for ocean health.
in asia alone they feed one billion people and provide a livelihood for millions more.
fifteen hundred species face extinction.
threats include global warming, pollution, over harvesting of fish, introduced species, diseases, and other human factors.
the 1998 el nino and 2004 tsunami took a heavy toll.
solutions are hard to find.
a world conservation blueprint is planned.
a global coral reef monitoring network was established.
satellite surveillance, trade restrictions, and marine sanctuaries are options.
heat tolerant algae are being studied.
****
coral reefs provide food and shelter for fish, protect shores from erosion, supply seafood for billions of people, and provide livelihoods for millions; but they are threatened by global warming, diseases, overfishing, mud, and pollution.
only 30% of the world's coral reefs are healthy; 20% have been destroyed and more than 58% are endangered.
more than 15,000 species face extinction unless effective conservation methods are implemented.
the u.s. is helping by improved monitoring, satellite surveillance, accepting an international treaty restricting trade, and $10 million in grants, while taiwan is creating artificial reefs with discarded utility poles and tires.
****
pfc.
lynndie england pleaded guilty to humiliating and assaulting prisoners at abu ghraib prison near baghad late in 2003.
in hearings, england said her actions were wrong but early in the trial she contradicted that statement.
judge col. pohl stopped her and said he did n't want her to plead guilty unless she thought she was.
military judges can not accept a guilty plea if the defendant does n't accept guilt.
if accepted, a military jury decides punishment and defendant gets the lesser of that or the plea agreed to by prosecutors.
defense attornies are capt.
crisps and rick hernandez.
****
pfc.
lynndie r. england, on trial at ft.
hood, texas on nine counts including conspiracy, dereliction of duty, maltreatment and indecent acts, pleaded guilty may 2, 2005 to seven of the counts.
the charges concern violation of the uniform code of military justice that occurred at the abu ghraib prison near baghdad, iraq in the fall of 2003.
under an agreement reached with military prosecutors, english would serve less than 11 years in prison.
if her plea is accepted by the military judge, col. james pohl, her sentencing will be referred to a military jury.
****
at a pre-trial hearing at fort hood, texas, connected with prisoner abuse at afghanistan's abu graib prison from october to december 2003, under an agreement with military prosecutors army reservist pfc.
lynndie england, 22, pleaded guilty to 7 of 9 counts, including conspiracy, dereliction of duty, maltreatment and indecent acts.
two charges were dropped.
the judge, col. james l. pohl, who heard cases of the other defendants, refused to recuse himself and accepted the plea.
england said she knew the abuse was morally and legally wrong but went along because of peer pressure from colleagues and then-boyfriend, spec.
charles graner.
****
pfc lynndie england, a west virginia army reservist involved in the abu ghraib prison photographs, pled guilty to two counts of conspiracy, four of mistreating prisoners, and one of indecency.
she has a history of mental problems and learning disabilities and trained as a records clerk, unaware of the geneva convention.
england said that she was doing as she was told, that she trusted her boyfriend, spec.
charles graner, the ringleader and her baby's father, because he was a prison guard, an mp, and older.
a military jury will convene on 3 may to recommend a sentence.
****
on 14 february 2005 in beirut, former lebanese prime minister rafik hariri and eight others were killed by a car bomb.
a previously unknown group, support and jihad in syria and lebanon, claimed responsibility on al-jazeera television, the group citing hariri's ties to a saudi arabia unsympathetic to their brothers.
however, many lebanese blamed syria, which regularly interfered in the affairs of lebanon, where it maintained 14,000 troops.
syria denied complicity.
france wanted an international investigation, this unwanted by both saudi arabia and lebanon.
the u.s. joined france in seeking the withdrawal of syrian troops from lebanon.
****
former lebanese prime minister rafik hariri, and at least 14 others, was killed in a poweful explosion in central beirut, monday, february 14.
hariri resigned late last year after heading five governments for more than 12 years.
he'd helped lebanon rebuild after 15 years of civil war.
well over 100,000 marched in a funeral parade, voicing opposition to syria which has been in the country since 1970 and currently has 14,000 troops there.
opposition leaders hold lebanon and syrian governments responsible for the bombing.
led by the u.s. and france, international pressure grows for syria to withdraw from lebanon.
****
former lebanese prime minister rafik hariri was killed by a suicide car bomb february 14, 2005 in beirut.
six of his body guards and 10 other were also killed with about 120 injured.
two islamic terrorist groups claimed responsibility but opposition leaders blamed the lebanese and syrian governments.
hariri opposed syrian intervention in the lebanese presidential term and was working to make a comeback in the may election.
the opposition, france, and the us called for the withdrawal of the syrian troops.
the opposition and france called for an international commission, while the opposition also demanded the prime minister's resignation.
****
former lebanese prime minister rafik hariri was killed in a suicide car bombing in beirut on 14 february at least 14 others were killed and about 120 injured in the blast that hit his motorcade.
a previously unknown islamic group has claimed responsibility.
the opposition leader blamed syria and demanded that syria withdraw its 14,000 troops still in lebanon.
there is also renewed international pressure for a syrian troop withdrawal.
syria condemned the attack and denied involvement.
well over 100,000 mourners attended the funeral.
hariri and the other victims were buried on the grounds of an unfinished mosque in beirut.
****
in february 2004, britain's food standards agency recalled 474 products containing sudan i, a potentially cancer causing colorant imported from india.
premier foods apparently mistakenly added chili powder contaminated with the red dye to worcester sauce made by them for crosse and blackwell, the sauce also incorporated into other recalled foods.
an italian company testing imports for sudan i uncovered the problem.
the european union banned the importation of chili powder containing sudan i in 2003, the offending ingredient supposedly predating the ban.
the british agency launched an unprecedented probe but also downplayed the risk of severe illness.
****
britain's food standards agency ( fsa) recalled 474 food products found to contain the carcinogenic sudan i red dye.
used to color solvents, waxes, petrol and shoe polish, it is illegal for use in food.
however, the risk of illness is estimated to be very small based on the concentrations used.
the food safety alert was issued february 18 after italian authorities discovered the dye in a batch of worcestershire sauce from england.
the recall affects 12 eu states and china.
the fsa investigation into how the dye found its way into the british food chain is focused on three companies.
****
red dye sudan i, approved for non-food use, was found in worchester sauce in 2005.
britain issued a safety alert on february 18 and began withdrawing products containing this sauce.
eventually 474 products were identified.
residents, restaurants, and retailers were notified.
the dye was banned by britain and the european union in 2003, but was discover in indian-produced chili powder put in the sauce and probably imported earlier.
this dye increases the risk of cancer, although that increase is very small.
products had been exported to european countries, north america, the caribbean, and china.
britain has begun an investigation.
****
britain's food standards agency ordered 474 foods recalled because they contain the dye sudan i, used to color products like oils and shoe polish.
the eu has banned its use in foods because of an increased, albeit small, risk of cancer.
the foods were all made with worcestershire sauce which contained the chili powder.
all chili powder imported since july 2003 must be certified free of the agent.
since worcestershire sauce takes a long time to mature, the powder probably entered britain before the ban.
britain ordered a thorough investigation.
the discovery has sparked an international food safety alert.
****
an explosion at a petrochemical plant on the songhua river in northeast china on nov. 13, 2005 threatened toxic benzene pollution of drinking water of harbin, urban population 3.8 million.
the songhua is a tributary of the heilong ( russian amur) river on the russian border.
china pledged to keep russian authorities informed of the movement of the benzene-polluted block.
harbin cut off its urban water supply nov. 23.
the populace was advised to avoid all contact with pollution.
water discharge from two reservoirs was increased to dilute a massive slick of pollutants.
authorities are investigating criminal responsibility for the catastrophe.
****
a petrochemical plant explosion on china's songhua river resulted in an 80-kilometer odorless, invisible slick of benzene, toxic to humans.
contingency plans included discharging reservoir water into the river to dilute the pollution, keep the current moving, and prevent the river from freezing.
these efforts helped the benzene concentration to decline.
the city of harbin, where the river provides drinking water for 3 million people, temporarily cut off its water supply, and residents stockpiled water.
china also warned russia of polluted tributary water.
officials summarized past shutdowns and punishments for similar pollution, vowing to take tougher measures in the future.
****
on november 13, 2005, an explosion at the jilin petrochemical company released 100 tons of pollutants, including high-density benzene and nitrobenzene, into the songhua river in ne china, to create a 50-mile slick of floating chemicals.
water quality was monitored constantly and active carbon added.
patrols enforced non-use by humans or animals.
china kept russia informed since the songhua joins the amur border river.
the songhua supplies drinking water for harbin, a city of over 3 million.
harbin cut off its water supply for four days.
pollutant density declined with sedimentation, adsorbtion, and dilution as tributaries and reservoirs added water.
****
explosions at a petrochemical plant on 13 november caused major water pollution by benzene and nitrobenzene on northeastern china?s songhua river.
the density was almost 30 times the standard; the polluted swath was 80 kilometers long.
the water supply was turned off in harbin, population about 4 million.
the pollution has injured no one because timely countermeasures were taken: the entry of pollutants was blocked, reservoir water was released to dilute thee pollutants, and monitoring was increased.
the plant was about 150 km from the chinese russian border.
the songhua river is called the amur river in russia.
****
on december 26, 2004, an 8.7 magnitude earthquake, the biggest in the world in 40 years, unleashed a tsunami that slammed into coastal communities from southern asia to africa, killing nearly 150,000 in 11 nations.
indonesia's death toll had reached 94,200 and was expected to top 100,000 on hardest-hit sumatra island, and 500,000 indonesians were left homeless.
sumatra was the focus of a massive international aid effort with foreign militaries, led by the us, flying in assistance.
on january 6, indonesia would host a summit of world leaders from 23 countries to discuss the aftermath of the disaster.
****
an 8.7 degree earthquake off sumatra island, followed by a killer tsunami, devastated parts of asia on 26 december 2004, killing nearly 150,000 in 11 nations.
this was the world's largest earthquake in 40 years.
foreign militaries led by the united states are assisting with relief efforts.
china sent a quake-rescue team to indonesia, where nearly 500,000 were rendered homeless.
australia and japan contributed millions of dollars and japan committed to help with reconstruction.
supplies were sent by china, bangladesh, uzbekistan, denmark, and switzerland.
indonesia plans to host 23 nations in a summit to discuss the aftermath of the disaster.
****
aid has begun to pour into indonesia, hardest hit by the december 26, 2004 tsunami.
this tsunami was caused by an earthquake off northern sumatra that registered 8.7 on the richter scale.
aceh province and north sumatra were hardest hit with more than 100,000 killed in sumatra and 500,000 homeless in aceh province.
offered aid included $2.62 million from china, $146 million and military teams from japan, $764 million from australia, humanitarian aid from bangladesh and uzbekistan, and uzbekistan transporting supplies from denmark and switzerland.
indonesia has scheduled a summit of world leaders for january 6.
****
a massive tsunami hit coastal communities from southern asia to africa on 26 december, killing at least 150,000 people in 11 countries.
it was caused by the biggest earthquake in 40 years, 8.7 on the richter scale, off indonesia's sumatra island.
indonesia was the hardest hit, with at least 90,000 dead.
and its aceh province was devastated with at least 500,00 homeless.
sri lanka and the maldives also suffered tremendous losses and damage.
international aid has been sent from a host of countries, including the us, japan, australia, bangladesh, uzbekistan, denmark, and switzerland.